{
  "answer": "**In Allama Iqbal's poem \"Mashriq mein usool deen ban jaate\" (Bang-e-Dara Part 3, Chapter 28), the principle described is the contrast between Eastern and Western approaches to innovation and progress.**\n\nThe single-paragraph poem states:\n\n> In the East, new Principles of Faith we decree,[^1]  \n> But in the West, it's new machines we see.  \n> But not a single one we get to keep,  \n> While there, from one, they go and fashion three.[^1]\n\nIqbal critiques how the East proclaims (\"decree\") abstract \"Principles of Faith\" (*usool-e-deen*) but fails to retain or build upon them effectively (\"not a single one we get to keep\"), while the West practically innovates in technology, multiplying inventions from one to three.[^1] This highlights a deeper philosophical principle: the East's stagnation in spiritual/religious ideation versus the West's dynamic material progress, urging Muslims to emulate productive action.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/28-mashriq-mein-usool-deen-ban-jaate/translation/#p-13a391).",
